[[File:赤砂崎公園 007.jpg|thumb|Akasunasaki Park, developed on both banks of the river mouth]]
The '''Togawa River''' (砥川) is a {{ill|river|ja|川}} in {{ill|Shimosuwa, Nagano|ja|下諏訪町}}, {{ill|Nagano Prefecture|ja|長野県}}, Japan. It is a {{ill|first-class river|ja|一級河川}} within the {{ill|Tenryū River|ja|天竜川}} water system.

== Geography ==
The river originates at {{ill|Wada Pass (Nagano)|ja|和田峠}}, located in the northern part of Shimosuwa Town. It joins its tributaries, the Higashimata River and the Fukuzawa River, before flowing into {{ill|Lake Suwa|ja|諏訪湖}} west of Shimosuwa's urban center.{{Sfn|Nichigai Associates|1991|p=668}}

== Tributaries ==
{{See|List of tributaries of the Tenryū River}}

== History ==
The river is known for its abundant springs, which have been used for {{ill|irrigation|ja|灌漑}} since ancient times. In {{ill|1846|ja|弘化}} (Kōka 3), Komegawa-Shio was excavated, and in {{ill|1708|ja|宝永}} (Hōei 5), Hagikura-Shio was similarly developed.

In {{ill|1900|ja|明治}} (Meiji 33), the '''Ochiai Power Plant''' was completed, marking the start of the electrification era in the Suwa region. This hydroelectric power plant, which sourced water from the Higashimata River, initially generated 60 kilowatts of electricity. Its capacity was later increased to 120 kilowatts in {{ill|1903|ja|明治36}} and 200 kilowatts in {{ill|1910|ja|明治43}}.<ref>{{Cite sign |author=Chubu Electric Power Suwa Energy Center |title=One Hundred Years of Electricity in the Suwa Region: Birthplace of Electricity in Suwa |type=Information Panel |location=Ochiai Power Plant |date=2000 }}</ref> In addition to Ochiai Power Plant, the '''Chogasawa Power Plant''' (250 kilowatts)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jepoc.or.jp/hydro/index.php?_w=usData&_x=detail2&pp=1&OwnerNo=004&AreaNo=04&RiverSys=4050&fd=1 |title=Chogasawa |website=Hydroelectric Power Plant Database |publisher=Electric Power Civil Engineering Association |accessdate=2022-01-23 }}</ref> and the '''Togawa Power Plant''' (490 kilowatts) also operate on the river.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jepoc.or.jp/hydro/index.php?_w=usData&_x=detail2&pp=3&OwnerNo=004&AreaNo=04&RiverSys=4050&fd=1 |title=Togawa |website=Hydroelectric Power Plant Database |publisher=Electric Power Civil Engineering Association |accessdate=2022-01-23 }}</ref>

Additionally, the riverbed of Togawa provided '''Togawa Cobblestones''', which were used as raw materials for {{ill|obsidian|ja|黒曜石}} in ancient times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pref.nagano.lg.jp/kyoiku/bunsho/kassei/documents/new.pdf |title=Comprehensive Guide to Shinshu Obsidian |publisher=Nagano Prefecture Board of Education |accessdate=2020-08-09}}</ref>

<gallery>
File:Ochiai power station (Nagano).jpg|Ochiai Power Plant<br/>Located at the confluence of the Togawa and Higashimata Rivers.
File:Chogasawa power station.jpg|Chogasawa Power Plant<br/>(on the Higashimata River)
File:Togawa power station (Nagano) survey.jpg|Togawa Power Plant
</gallery>

== Shimosuwa Dam Project ==
A dam project was originally proposed, but the plan was canceled following Governor {{ill|Yasuo Tanaka|ja|田中康夫}}'s {{ill|No-Dam Declaration|ja|脱ダム宣言}} in Nagano Prefecture.

