The river is known for its abundant springs, which have been used for {{ill|irrigation|ja|灌漑|qq=draft|qq=draft}} since ancient times. In {{ill|1846|ja|弘化|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Kōka 3), Komegawa-Shio was excavated, and in {{ill|1708|ja|宝永|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Hōei 5), Hagikura-Shio was similarly developed.

In {{ill|1900|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (Meiji 33), the '''Ochiai Power Plant''' was completed, marking the start of the electrification era in the Suwa region. This hydroelectric power plant, which sourced water from the Higashimata River, initially generated 60 kilowatts of electricity. Its capacity was later increased to 120 kilowatts in {{ill|1903|ja|明治36|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and 200 kilowatts in {{ill|1910|ja|明治43|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.<ref>{{Cite sign |author=Chubu Electric Power Suwa Energy Center |title=One Hundred Years of Electricity in the Suwa Region: Birthplace of Electricity in Suwa |type=Information Panel |location=Ochiai Power Plant |date=2000 }}</ref> In addition to Ochiai Power Plant, the '''Chogasawa Power Plant''' (250 kilowatts)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jepoc.or.jp/hydro/index.php?_w=usData&_x=detail2&pp=1&OwnerNo=004&AreaNo=04&RiverSys=4050&fd=1 |title=Chogasawa |website=Hydroelectric Power Plant Database |publisher=Electric Power Civil Engineering Association |accessdate=2022-01-23 }}</ref> and the '''Togawa Power Plant''' (490 kilowatts) also operate on the river.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jepoc.or.jp/hydro/index.php?_w=usData&_x=detail2&pp=3&OwnerNo=004&AreaNo=04&RiverSys=4050&fd=1 |title=Togawa |website=Hydroelectric Power Plant Database |publisher=Electric Power Civil Engineering Association |accessdate=2022-01-23 }}</ref>

Additionally, the riverbed of Togawa provided '''Togawa Cobblestones''', which were used as raw materials for {{ill|obsidian|ja|黒曜石|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in ancient times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pref.nagano.lg.jp/kyoiku/bunsho/kassei/documents/new.pdf |title=Comprehensive Guide to Shinshu Obsidian |publisher=Nagano Prefecture Board of Education |accessdate=2020-08-09}}</ref>

